  <subsection><title>Logarithm Laws</title>
  <p> 
    In <xref ref="sec-exp-intro"/>, we reviewed the main exponent laws that help us to simplify and re-write exponential expressions in simpler ways. 
    Logarithmic expressions also have a similar set of laws that help us re-write logarithmic expressions:

  <assemblage>
    <title>Logarithm Laws</title>
    <p>
      For any postitive numbers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> the following is true:
    </p>
    <p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p> Product Law
          <md number="yes">
            \ln(xy) = \ln x + \lny 
          </md>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p> Quotient Law
          <md number="yes">
            \ln\left(\frac{x}{y}\right) = \ln x - \lny 
          </md>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p> Power Law
          <md number="yes">
            \ln\left(x^y\right) = y\ln x 
          </md>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
  </assemblage>

<p>
  Similar Laws are also true for other logarithms (with other bases) but we will focus on <m>\ln x</m> (with base <m>e</m>).
</p>


<p>
It is important to understand these laws, and it is also important to understand some common errors that students make when applying these laws:
<ol>
  <li>
    <p>
      Logarithms are <alert>not</alert> distributive into their own arguments. In other words, <m>\ln (x \pm y) \neq \ln x \pm \ln y.</m>
    </p>
  </li>
    <li>
    <p>
      To apply the power law, only the \textit{argument} of the logarithm should be raised to an exponent. 
      In other words, the Power Law would \textit{not} apply to logarithms written in the form of <m>(\ln x)^a</m> or <m>\ln^a(x).</m>
    </p>
  </li>
    <li>
    <p>
      In order to apply either the Product Rule or Quotient Rule, the logarithm must not have a coefficient. 
      If the logarithm has a coefficient (other than 1), you must first apply the Power Law before you can apply either of the other two laws
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
</p>



\textcolor{blue}{Example: before the checkpoint(s), probably should put some examples of logarithm laws being used. The examples should show each of the laws working in "both directions" (i.e. expanding and collapsing) \\
\begin{itemize}
    \item $\ln (6) + \ln(4.5)=\ln (27)$
    \item $\ln a + \ln b + \ln c=\ln (abc) $
    \item $\ln (48)-\ln (3) = \ln (16)$
    \item $\ln x - \ln y = \ln (\frac{x}{y})$
    \item $\ln \left(\frac{a}{bc}\right)=\ln a - \ln b - \ln c$
    \item $\ln (5^3)=3\ln 5$
    \item $\ln(\sqrt[3]{5})=\frac{1}{3}\ln (5)$
    \item $3\ln (x+2)=\ln (x+2)^3$
\end{itemize}}

  <exercise>
